With the World Health Organizationâs declaration of the Covid-19 pandemic in March 2020, the looming question has been whether or not to postpone our July wedding. A difficult decision before us, we wanted to take a quick look at the numbers to give some confidence to our decision,1 while keeping in mind that there are two key dimensions to consider for a just decision: (1) health and (2) geopolitics.

To be clear, weâre not modeling or projecting anything here. We only wanted to look at the data ourselves2 since we couldnât find our questions answered out there. Since we figured that weâre not the only nerds in this email list, we stitched the graphs together for you.

We used data collated by the New York Times (yes, NYT appears to be the cleanest and most complete data source at the moment) and the European CDC from mid-February to May 3rd to get a picture of Covid-19 trajectories in the United States and selected European countries, respectively. We computed the cumulative cases and deaths over the course of the pandemic, incidence (cases per day), and mortality (deaths per day) and adjusted for population size for each state or country.

Letâs take a look.

The (Not So) United States

Indeed, there have been a lot of deaths in recent weeksâ¦

This graph shows the number of deaths per day in the US. For comparison, at its peak, Covid-19 caused more than 2,000 fatalities per day when in normal times, weâd expect about 7,700 deaths each day on average. Thatâs over 25%!

Note the dips in the graph. These are weekends and, subsequently, pauses in data collection. Because of these idiosyncracies in reporting, all the following figures show values for the past 7 days.

So, this graph is a mess. But we see a few interesting trends.

New York and New Jersey are moving together. Massachusetts is coming to get them. All that is unsurprising given their geographical proximity and interconnections.

We also see plateauing. We can surmise that this mirrors the stay-home orders in various states. Good examples are Washington, New York, and Michigan (good luck finding this one).

Looking at cases alone is not enough: case reporting is highly variable depending on testing protocols and resources.

Here, we look at total deaths since the beginning of the pandemic. The story is the same for New York, New Jersey, and Massachusetts. Pennsylvania, Illinois, Indiana, and Maryland make a motley crew walking the middle path, while the rest seem to be following Washingtonâs trajectory.

What about Europe?

Itâs easier to tell. Theyâre all roughly behaving the same, apart from Sweden and the UK. The Covid-19 slowdown potentially induced by lockdowns is much more pronounced as shown by the sharp decrease in new cases over the last 20 days.

Adjusting for population shows that all of the countries are roughly hanging out in the same ballpark with the exception of Germany, who either has a magic trick or is reporting deaths differently.

Interestingly, we can see that France initially followed in the footsteps of Italy. However, having started strong lockdown earlier in their trajectory, has curbed deaths and will likely end up with fewer.

And now, what weâve all been waiting forâ¦Europe vs.Â US

New York got hit later than European countries, but hard and fast. Itâs astounding. We can see that itâs struggling to rein in the virus as fast as its counterparts.

California and Washington appear to be hanging out in a plateau, while Italy and France seem to have decidedly reduced the activity of the disease.

France and Italy report overall a higher level of mortality in the population compared to California and Washington, even though they seem to be in the same arena in terms of case count. This may be due to differences in reporting of Covid-19 cases, and potentially deaths.

So what?

Based on the downward trends that we see and assuming that there is no strong rebound, there is some hope that, on the 4th of July, the threat of Covid-19 will have been diminished.3 On top of the uncertainty of the disease, there is the uncertainty of international travel and border restrictions.

In truth, we made the decision to postpone our wedding at least two weeks ago. As you can see, this was when we all were continuing the climb to the top. Of course, we still believe postponement to be the right decision.4

Over these past couple of weeks, amidst our search for the sword that seals the darkness5, we have confirmed the changes with each of our vendors and made arrangements for the 14th of July 2021.

We canât wait to laugh and dance with all of you beautiful humans!
